[B] Pfizer vaccine
Date: Fri 11 Mar 2022
Source: CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy) [abridged, edited]
https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2022/03/chinese-provincial-capital-locks-down-countrys-covid-cases-rise


Receiving 2 doses of Pfizer vaccine showed moderate to good protection in 2 age-groups of children, researchers reported today [11 Mar 2022] in Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report (MMWR). They based their findings on an ongoing cohort survey that tracks infections in children ages 6 months to 17 years in 4 states (http://dx.doi.org/10.15585/mmwr.mm7111e1).

For children ages 5-11, vaccine effectiveness was moderate, at 31% for prevention of symptomatic and asymptomatic disease. For kids ages 12-15, the vaccine doses were 59% effective.

Researchers said wide and overlapping confidence intervals suggest the estimates might not be significantly different and are similar to a recent vaccine effectiveness report of 45%-51% against emergency department and urgent care visits for omicron infections across the 2 age-groups.

The authors said kids infected with omicron despite having received 2 vaccine doses spent an average of one-half day less in bed than unvaccinated study participants. "All eligible children and adolescents should remain up to date with recommended COVID-19 vaccinations," they wrote.

In other US developments:
- White House officials yesterday [10 Mar 2022] warned that key pandemic programs could run out of funds if Congress doesn't quickly authorize USD 15.6 billion in new funding for the efforts, according to Politico (https://www.politico.com/news/2022/03/10/more-covid-aid-uncertain-00016212).
- The Transportation Security Agency yesterday [10 Mar 2022] announced that the mask requirement for planes and public transportation will be extended through 18 Apr 2022, according to the Associated Press. The rule was originally set to end next week, on 18 Mar 2022 (https://bit.ly/3pYW4CD).
- Nursing home resident COVID-19 booster rates in about one-third of US states lag the national average, with 3 states -- Florida, Arizona, and Nevada -- yet to reach an average of 60% boosted in each facility, according to ABC News (https://abcn.ws/3w1ActW).

[Byline: Lisa Schnirring]

